The paper deals with a search algorithm for big data sets in astronomy and biology, which involves approximate search and takes advantage of geometric properties of the data. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories related to data management, data structures, computer vision, machine learning, and algorithms. Specifically, cs.DB (databases), cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), and cs.CV (computer vision and pattern recognition) seem relevant due to the focus on data processing and analysis. Additionally, cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.LG (machine learning) could be relevant due to the use of GPU acceleration and the potential for extending the algorithm to k-nearest neighbors search.
